## Purpose of This Blueprint

This document serves as the single source of truth for:

* Design of a flexible, scalable data model for the product catalog  
* Defining upstream APIs for catalog management and downstream contracts for quoting, checkout, invoicing, provisioning, and other domains.  
* Outlining the user workflows in PCC—new product/group creation, SKU generation, attribute setup and experimentation.  
* Aligning stakeholders (Product, Engineering, Design) on engineering terminology, and next steps.

# Problem

As part of the GTM Speed initiative, we must overhaul our New Product Introduction (NPI) process so that it is:

* Intuitive for LOB Product Managers (PMs) and business users  
* Transparent for engineers who build and integrate downstream systems  
* Lightweight to operate without deep technical expertise

## Current Challenges

* Fragmented workflows: PMs must coordinate with engineering teams to define products, prices, and digital‐goods entitlements.  
* Unclear Definitions: Product and SKU terminology is used interchangeably without much thought causing confusion between LBP, Finance and LOBs.  
* Rigid data model: Existing catalog schema makes it difficult to add or override attributes at the product or SKU level. For example, a bundled SKU can’t override the Product attribute.  
* Heavy‐lift updates: Changing email templates, rules, or presentation configurations often requires code changes.  
* Experimentation: Experimenting with offering one set of features to one group of customers vs offering more features to another group of customers is a challenge for the Premium team. Today, this is done by introducing a new product, which is a slow process due to the vast number of fields involved.  
* Lack of transparency and visibility: Product managers who do not actively work with the product catalog team can easily miss the full set of products that they are responsible for.   
  * For example, without tribal knowledge, it is hard to know that the LinkedIn Learning Field product is split into 9 separate products. When a digital good or new feature is added, the new feature needs to be added to all 9 products under the Learning umbrella. 

## Desired Capabilities

* **Experimentation Support**: Enable low-cost dynamic experimentation by allowing the creation of variant SKUs to test price points, digital goods quantities, bundle configurations, email templates, product name or feature sets across customer segments.   
* **Bundling and Reporting**: Support composition-based bundling (e.g., “Ads/Jobs Bundle”) with per-component quantities, and generate accurate reporting on bundle performance and revenue recognition.  
* **Self-Served Lifecycle Management**: Provide a clear, intuitive self-service UI for product managers to create, update, or sunset products and SKUs without requiring engineering intervention.  
* **Master Data Management (MDM)**: Maintain a centralized source of truth for all product catalog data with strong governance, versioning, and consistency controls.

## Key Definitions

| Term | Definition |
| :---- | :---- |
| Product Folder | Top-level category representing a set of related products, tailored to a line of business or market segment. The benefit for LOB PM is to be able to efficiently manage the products in a folder setup. |
| Product | A specific market offering under a Product Folder, with at least one SKU but potentially with multiple SKUs representing variants. |
| SKU | The basic sellable unit, defined by attributes such as billing frequency, platform, channel, and bundle ID. |
| Bundle | A composite product composed of multiple SKUs with specified quantities, sold as a single entity. |
| Price | A collection of price points (currency & amount) associated with one or more SKUs. |
| Attribute | A configurable property at any catalog level, such as email templates, digital goods mappings, pricing rules, or presentation settings. |
| PCB | Product Catalog Backend |

# Solution

In order to handle all the requirements specified above, we build a data model which solves all the above use cases. This document discusses more details of the data model, provides an extensive list of examples of how actual products are set up and what the various use cases look like.

## Why a Hierarchical DAG Catalog Structure?

The product catalog is organized as a **Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG)** with three primary layers: **Product Folder → Product → SKU**. This structure supports **inheritance of attributes** from parent to child, with the ability to **override** specific fields at lower levels. This design enables both business agility and system scalability in the following ways:

### Business Benefits

1. **Experimentation Enablement**  
   * The hierarchy allows SKUs to act as isolated, testable variants of a consistent product definition.  
   * **Product** becomes the scope of experimentation (e.g., "Premium Career"), while **SKU** serves as the unit of experimentation (e.g., "Premium Career – Annual – Android – v2").  
   * This enables A/B testing on pricing, features, or presentation across customer segments without duplicating product logic.  
2. **Composable Bundling and Reporting**  
   * Individual SKUs can be grouped into **hard** **bundles** while still referencing shared product-level attributes.  
   * This supports **clean separation of concerns**: SKUs define variant-specific fulfillment (e.g., quantities, platform), while the product defines shared characteristics.  
   * Performance and revenue reporting can be performed at both SKU and aggregated product levels and sliced across any SKU attributes/dimensions. Usually, this would be done at Product level, but use cases like bundles will require SKU level reporting.  
3. **Self-Served Lifecycle Management**  
   * Lifecycle operations (e.g., sunsetting, feature updates) applied at the **product level** automatically cascade to child SKUs—reducing manual effort. Note that standalone SKUs can also be sunset.  
   * SKUs may override specific lifecycle states if necessary (e.g., keep one variant active for legacy customers).

### System Design Advantages

1. **Attribute Reuse and DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself) Principle**  
   * Shared metadata, configurations, and business rules can be defined once at the **Product** level and inherited by all descendant SKUs.  
   * This reduces duplication and enforces consistency across variants.  
2. **Flexible and Scalable Configuration Management**  
   * New SKU variants (e.g., for experiments or new channels) can be introduced under existing products without restructuring the catalog.  
   * This supports rapid iteration and growth without sacrificing structure.  
3. **Clear and Intuitive Data Structure**  
   * A parent-child hierarchy mirrors how product managers and analysts conceptualize offerings.  
   * This logical structure simplifies both UI presentation (e.g., a collapsible tree view) and downstream processing (e.g., configuration resolution, reporting).

## Data Model Overview

### Hierarchy

![][image1]  
The catalog is structured as a directed acyclic graph (DAG): Product Folder → Product → SKU. Each level inherits attributes from its parent and may override specific fields to support variant behavior.

### Catalog Composition

Every “SKU” in PCC is a composite of multiple configurable layers upstream and downstream.

1. Product Folder (e.g. “Premium Generic”)  
2. Product (e.g. “Premium Career”)  
3. Bundles that combine several SKUs into a single offering  
4. All Attributes such as  
   * Pricing (multi‐currency, multi‐tier)  
   * Digital Goods (entitlements, licenses)  
   * Email templates (renewals, billing notifications)  
   * Invoice visibility and rules  
   * Presentation configurations (URLs, descriptions, UI behavior)  
   * Bizapps related attributes \- tax code, revenue id, gl account assignment

## Product Configuration Center User Workflows

1. Users have the option to either create a new Product, or create more variants of the existing product (SKUs).  
2. Users have the option to experiment across variants of an existing product.  
3. Users can create and update prices for a set of SKUs together. 

### New Product Folder Setup Workflow

1. The user lands on PCC and goes through a page which lists existing product folders.  
2. If the existing groups and their corresponding attributes do not fulfill the exact needs of business, the user creates a new Product Folder. The Product Folder is deployed to EI and Prod environments.

### New Product Setup Workflow

1. The user lands on PCC and goes through a page which lists existing product groups and selects the appropriate Product Folder.  
2. The user chooses the wizard to create a new Product.  
3. As a part of product creation, the user goes through a flow which asks the user for the attributes which are allowed as per PRD rules. Note that PCC constrains and controls what attributes can be added at this point, the PRD will define these with the current set of use cases in further detail.   
4. Product is deployed to EI and PROD.   
5. Note that Product attributes can be altered at any point by a user.

### New SKU Setup Workflow 

#### Creation of Standalone Product 

1. Users are asked a list of supported dimensions : Supported Billing Frequency, Platform, Channel.  
2. Once the user enters the information, the system auto generates the SKUs based on the entered list of multipliers.

| Product  | SKU | User options (Attributes) | Attributes |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Premium Career | SKU\_1 | Monthly, Desktop, Online, Control | Price 1 , DG (inherited from Product level), Presentation configs (overridden potentially) |
|  | SKU\_2 | Annual, Desktop, Online, Control | Price 2 , DG (inherited from Product level), Presentation configs (overridden potentially) |

#### Creation of Hard Bundle 

1. Users create a new Product for the Bundle. For example : Premium Small Business \- Ads/Jobs Bundle.  
2. Users are asked questions such as: What products would you like to add to this Product Bundle.  
3. Once the user enters the list of products, ask them about the other supported dimensions: Supported Billing Frequency, Platform, Channel.  
4. Once all information is entered the system generates a list of SKUs for the Bundle SKU (Premium Small Business \- Ads/Jobs Bundle) AND the products which are part of the bundle by attaching a new bundle id to the SKU dimensions. Note that this workflow will need to gather more information from the user on the various dimensions that the user wants to experiment on.

#### Experimentation 

1. The user shows the intent to perform experimentation on a Product.   
2. Note that experimentation will only ever be supported within the scope of a Product.  
3. The user workflow asks user some questions:  
   1. Which attributes do you want to experiment on: Prices, Digital Goods, Emails etc.  
   2. The system then auto generates more SKUs for the Product which correspond to the requested set of attribute values in step a above.  
   3. Note that one of the dimensions for the new set of SKUs will be Lix Key and Treatment. These can be used by LOBs to target the particular SKU to users in need for the particular attributes. Also Lix will be owned by the LOBs and assigned to the SKU. LBP will only deal with SKUs and not deal with lix.

## Handling Existing flows

### LOB Flows

The typical use case for a Line of business is to provide a set of dimensions and let the platform construct the applicable Quotes for a user. The new data model for product catalog will **not impact** the line of business flows. The existing systems can continue to function as is without needing any change or being SKU Id aware. Eventually, we will expect all LOBs to move to directly using SKUs instead of Products.

| Flow | Definition | Example |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Offer Eligibility  | Determine if a member is eligible for an offer | No sku impact as such today. |
| Purchase Eligibility Filter | Determine which SKUs a member is eligible to purchase | New API being worked upon. SKU would need to have upgrade/downgrade paths in future. Can be a SKU level attribute depending on use cases in future, no impact today. |
| Quote Creation | LOB passes the input params to generate a quote. Note that the input params would contain a set of SKUs for which quotes can be generated. | Premium passes the product id, channel, platform, billing frequency, variant id into the create proposal tree APIs. No changes needed. Once SKU is supported by Premium, SKU will be used by Quoting and Pricing layers. |

### LBP Entity Setup

Today, the various transactional entities within LBP such as Quote, Order, Contract, Invoice are composed of lines which have dimensions such as:

1. Billing Frequency  
2. Channel  
3. Product\_id  
4. Bundle\_id  
5. Platform

With the introduction of a SKU Id in Product Catalog, there is scope to simplify the various transactional entities to simply refer to the SKUId on a order line/contract line/quote line instead of the current set of dimensions which are duplicated across domains. In the final state, the vision is to move all downstream entities to be based on SKU Id, simplifying the data setup. Product Catalog APIs can be queries to figure out the dimensions if needed by a domain. 

Having said that, this migration can happen over a period of time. On day 0, we don’t foresee a need to move to this model, and the domains can continue to function as is without needing any changes. Note that when a functionality is requested by LOB which requires the domain to be SKU aware, the domain will need to store the SKU Id on its transactional entities. So we foresee this migration to be more use case driven over time.

### LBP Domain Flows

1. Conceptually, LBP Domains always operate on a SKU level, because only a SKU can flow across domains.   
2. However, given the legacy setup, the current state is that all LBP domains access the Product directly. This need not change immediately.   
3. If the domain needs the capability to define SKU level overrides, they should update the attribute lookup to lookup based on the SKU Id instead of the Product Id. 

Note that there are two possibilities with how a domain stores domain product attributes:

1. Stored in product-catalog-backend database. Example: Domain Presentation Configurations.  
2. Stored in a domain owned database. Example: Digital Goods, Pricing.

| Pricing | Pricing to determine Price for SKU  | Prices are looked up based on the SKU |

| Admin Center | Admin center to determine Urls for the SKU on the contract. Admin center to determine if SKU is visible on the Admin center. | Domain Code calls PCB to determine urls. Domain Code calls PCB to determine SKU visibility.  The current system calls with a composite key: \<Product, Variant Id\> |
| Invoicing  | For an Order composed of multiple lines, given a line, determine if it should show up on the invoice. | Domain Code calls PCB to determine if the product is visible on an invoice. The current system calls with a composite key: \<Product, Variant Id\> |
| Provisioning | Given the SKU, determine the Digital Goods which should be fulfilled as a part of provisioning.  | Domain Code checks the SKU to Digital Good mapping internally. Since Provisioning does not lookup based on SKU today, they can continue to lookup the digital goods by product\_id. Note that if there comes a time when provisioning wants to be SKU aware w.r.t. DG mapping, provisioning can map the new DG to SKU Id instead of Product Id or use the \<ProductId, Variant Id\> Pair to access the SKU. |
| Emails | Given a SKU, determine the Email template to use for the SKU. Renewal Email Offer Expiry email Billing Email Given a SKU, determine the configurable names, descriptions, urls to show for it on the various emails Different names based on SKU | Domain code calls product catalog backend to determine the email config value given the SKU name. As we build the PCB pipeline with an email server, it should be SKU based. |
| Contracts | Should product be aggregated for renewals/next charge RTCD configs for renewals | Domain Code calls PCB to determine if the product is a primary product for contract aggregation. The current system calls with a composite key: \<Product, Variant Id\> |
| CSP | Should cancel option show up for the product on CSP. | Domain Code calls PCB to determine if the product is a primary product for CSP. |
| Reporting | Eventually Reporting should use SKU Id to drive the logic for metrics and join the SKU Id to the dimensions table to determine the segments to slice and dice on. | Meanwhile, reporting scripts can continue to depend on the existing logic. Product\_id, bundle\_id, channel, billing frequency etc. can be used for reporting pipelines. |
| Bizapps | Bizapps should eventually move to SKU Id based setup mapping although they can continue to look at the existing entities in near future unless they need SKU differentiation in revenue recognition. | While Bizapps can continue to work as is, in the long run for handling bundles, it might be beneficial for them to move SKU ID, note that it will be a larger migration where all domains will have to support the SKU Id concept. |

We expect very similar handling logic to show up for field flows as they get onboarded to PCC.

# Implementation Discussions

### Attribute Types

[Attributes](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1KEOU7JLts_kBsMYRIVrkFKdiJa4ODTioDuigdAmZp7M/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.u8xz19qsa6i) in the product catalog are classified into two types based on ownership and where they are stored:

* **Hosted Attributes:**  
  * These are managed and stored within the PCB store.  
  * Typically include metadata and presentation configurations used during checkout and admin workflows.  
  * Examples: Checkout URLs, invoice visibility flags, description strings, presentation settings, email template mappings.  
* **External Attributes:**  
  * These are defined and managed by downstream systems but need to be discoverable through PCC for configuration and referencing.  
  * PCC stores mappings and references but the underlying values are maintained in external services.  
  * Examples:  
    * **Digital Goods**: Entitlement groups, quantity of goods to be provisioned, license IDs.  
    * **Pricing**: Multi-currency price points, promotional configurations, eligibility filters tied to SKU via Prices.\*\* multi‐currency price points (SKU‐level)

In order to decide which option suits the domain, we base it off the complexity and usage patterns of the domain attributes. For domains like Pricing and Digital Goods, the complex storage and usage patterns warrant more scalable designs as opposed to hosted attributes. The process to determine this would be to start off with hosted attributes and if it does not fulfill the use cases, move to external storage options. Note: Any attribute on PCC requires that it can only be created, updated, or deleted via PCC.
